"Word up" is a slang phrase usually used as an exclamation or interjection. Though quite current, its origins are in black English of the 1980s. It has a few different meanings such as a general greeting, more or less equivalent to "Hello!" or "What's happening?" "What's the word?", "What's up?" – very much like the ubiquitous "Whassup?". Word up can also mean "Listen up!" or "Pay attention!". Often, it is an expression of approval, admiration or appreciation - and yes; it can mean "Yes, you're so right!", "I agree!" – said when someone has stated the truth or said something profound or meaningful. In New York City, there is this new slang that has arisen in Jamaica, Queens, in which people say "Word ON!" It is thought to have started after the huge club promoter Big Lou said it one day to his friend. It is the word on the street, no pun intended.